               <msContents>
                  <summary>The third of four volumes of the <title>Siyar al-Mutaʼakhkhirīn</title> (Review of Modern Times), with (<ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6631"><idno>Persian MS 150</idno></ref>, an unrelated volume added to complete the set, but uniform with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6632">151</ref>, and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6634">153</ref>).
                     The author <persName xml:lang="en" type="standard">Ghulām Husain Khān Ṭabaṭāḅāī (b. 1727 or 8) </persName> composed this general history of the Indian empire spanning the death of the Mughal Emperor <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard" key="person_6178410" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/6178410/" role="subject" change="#role-assignment">‘Alamgīr I</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1707">1707</date>‏ until <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1781">1195 AH (1781 CE)</date>.
                     Since the author relates many eyewitness accounts, historians regard it as a preeminent source on 18th-century <country ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/135375457">India</country>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_152-item1">
                     <author key="person_54543418" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/54543418/">
                        <persName xml:lang="en" type="standard">Ghulām Husain Khān, Ṭabaṭāḅāī, b. 1727 or 8</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">غلام حسين بن هدايت علی خان بن السيد عليم الله بن السيد فيض الله الطباطبائی الحسينی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_9519" change="#ids-cleanup">Siyar al-mutaʼakhkhirīn</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_9519" change="#ids-cleanup">سير المتأخرين</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmalla"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus>
                        بود که باقر علیخان را استظباری بقوت شوکت آصف جاهی متخقق است.
                     </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="266a" to="266a"> برگ ۲۶۶ر (folio 266a):</locus>
                        ایزد تعالی او را و چنین بزرگان را سلامت نگاهدارد که باعث نزول برکات الهی و یادگاراسلاف کرام‌ند.
                     </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="en">No colophon</colophon>
                     <note><persName role="trl" type="pseudonym">'Nota-Manus' (pseudonym of <addName type="alt">M. Raymond</addName>, a. k. a. <addName type="alt">'Haji Mustapha'</addName>, d. 1791)</persName> translated the first volume into English in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1789">1789</date>, but died before its completion, based upon which <persName role="trl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/311403069" key="person_311403069">Colonel John Briggs (d. 1875)</persName> revised and expanded the translation for the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/144665249" role="publisher" key="person_144665249">Oriental Translation Fund</orgName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1832">1832</date>.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of <material>paper</material> probably handmade in <country cert="medium" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/135375457">India</country>, with endleaves of the same. Laid lines ~ 1mm apart; no discernible chain lines.</support>
                        <extent><measure unit="folio" quantity="266"> 266 folios (ff. x + 266 + iv)</measure>  
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>246</height>
                              <width>162</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>190</height>
                              <width>101</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="original">
                           <p>Foliated in Hindu-Arabic numerals on the upper centres of the a sides by the scribe in red <material>ink</material>.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">
                           <p>Modern foliation in pencilled Arabic numerals starting with the table of contents on the upper-left corners on every 10th folio of the a sides.</p>
                           <p>Note that this record follows the original Hindu-Arabic numerals.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <catchwords>Catchwords thoughout on the lower left corners of the b sides.</catchwords>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>In good condition. Bound a bit tight. White salts on the exterior leather due to prolonged exposure to moisture.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="14">Written in 1 column with 14 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">miṣṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">
                        Written in a clear nasta‘liq hand in black <material>ink</material> with subheaders in red.
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <list>
                        <item><label>Table of Contents:</label> copied in another hand on the initial <locus from="ivb" to="ixb">the fourth to ninth flyleaves (ff. ivb–ixb)</locus>.</item>
                        <item>
                           <label>Bookplates:</label> <locus from="left_paste-down" to="left_paste-down">left paste-down,</locus> 
                           <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with shelf mark <q xml:lang="en">2/E</q>, and <q xml:lang="en">Bland MSS No. 374</q>.
                        </item>
                     </list>                           
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1785" notAfter="1825"><p>
                        Sewn all-along on five cords that are frayed and put down on the second to the first and last flyleaves. Twined Islamic-style chevron endbands are missing (but present on the related volumes), edges coloured yellow.
                        Bound in a British-Indian hybrid style, tight-backed in full red-brown goatskin <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material> without a flap (Type III binding as per Déroche), with five raised bands and uneven squares at the edges.. 
                        Internal doublures of the smooth red goatskin <material>leather</material>, the excess width of which is put down on the first and last flyleaves, and decorated with a strips of paper with serrated zig-zag cuts adhered over top.
                        Titled <title>"SEIR. AL. MÓTAKHERĪN VOL. III</title> in <material>gold</material> on the spine, uniformly with the other volumes.</p>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                           <height>252</height>
                           <width>171</width>
                           <depth>32</depth>
                        </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>In good condition, but exterior scuffed.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc> 
               </physDesc>
